00:03:23.890 --> 00:03:26.710
- So this is a symposium
about the undiscovered,

00:03:26.710 --> 00:03:28.270
what we don't know.

00:03:28.270 --> 00:03:29.920
And we've heard
a couple of talks

00:03:29.920 --> 00:03:32.587
this morning that
elaborate on the concept,

00:03:32.587 --> 00:03:34.420
and that have provided
us a couple of really

00:03:34.420 --> 00:03:37.390
exciting examples of
how in science, thinking

00:03:37.390 --> 00:03:40.390
about technology, we can expand
the way we look at things,

00:03:40.390 --> 00:03:43.090
and think new, different
thoughts about what

00:03:43.090 --> 00:03:46.320
might be out there.

00:03:46.320 --> 00:03:49.850
But unfortunately when it
comes to climate change,

00:03:49.850 --> 00:03:53.060
there is a ghastly
certainty in the science

00:03:53.060 --> 00:03:55.190
of what we know about
the climate changes

00:03:55.190 --> 00:03:57.560
that the planet will
witness in absence

00:03:57.560 --> 00:04:03.150
of a dramatic, near-term action
to retool our global economy.

00:04:03.150 --> 00:04:05.810
It's a message that
none of us want to hear.

00:04:05.810 --> 00:04:09.830
But it is the clear-eyed
reality of our situation.

00:04:15.720 --> 00:04:18.420
This is a graphic representation
of global temperature changes

00:04:18.420 --> 00:04:20.940
from 1880 to 2015.

00:04:20.940 --> 00:04:23.250
It provides a
striking illustration

00:04:23.250 --> 00:04:25.650
of the increase of
temperatures over time,

00:04:25.650 --> 00:04:30.734
and the accelerating pace of
new high-temperature records.

00:04:30.734 --> 00:04:32.900
Of course, climate change
is more complex than this.

00:04:32.900 --> 00:04:34.700
It's not just temperatures.

00:04:34.700 --> 00:04:37.250
And we've been studying,
as a scientific community

00:04:37.250 --> 00:04:39.530
and certainly in broader
communities such as my own

00:04:39.530 --> 00:04:42.680
in policy, trying to think about
how to capture and understand

00:04:42.680 --> 00:04:45.560
some of the problems inherent in
climate change for many decades

00:04:45.560 --> 00:04:46.060
now.

00:04:49.400 --> 00:04:53.060
A few weeks ago, this
knowledge was synthesized

00:04:53.060 --> 00:04:55.460
in a report released by
the Intergovernmental Panel

00:04:55.460 --> 00:04:57.510
on Climate Change, which
I suspect many of you

00:04:57.510 --> 00:04:59.630
at least have heard about.

00:04:59.630 --> 00:05:02.390
This report synthesized
thousands of papers

00:05:02.390 --> 00:05:04.910
on our scientific understanding
of the likely impacts

00:05:04.910 --> 00:05:08.320
of climate change under
different levels of warming.

00:05:08.320 --> 00:05:11.230
The report concludes
that even an additional 1

00:05:11.230 --> 00:05:14.140
degree of warming from
where we are today, by 2030

00:05:14.140 --> 00:05:16.750
could expose hundreds
of millions of people

00:05:16.750 --> 00:05:18.820
to dangerous climate
risks, stemming

00:05:18.820 --> 00:05:22.600
from extreme temperatures,
floods, rising sea

00:05:22.600 --> 00:05:24.520
levels, and more.

00:05:24.520 --> 00:05:26.770
It would endanger ecosystems
and threaten species

00:05:26.770 --> 00:05:28.000
with extinction.

00:05:28.000 --> 00:05:31.870
It would likely wipe out
99% of the remaining coral

00:05:31.870 --> 00:05:34.790
reefs on our planet.

00:05:34.790 --> 00:05:38.370
And that is for 1 additional
degree from today,

00:05:38.370 --> 00:05:41.720
to warming of roughly 2 degrees
above pre-industrial levels.

00:05:41.720 --> 00:05:44.270
Without rapid new action,
we could be on course

00:05:44.270 --> 00:05:46.880
to a warming of up
to 4 degrees Celsius

00:05:46.880 --> 00:05:49.220
above pre-industrial
levels, with which

00:05:49.220 --> 00:05:51.140
is a change that is
similar in magnitude

00:05:51.140 --> 00:05:53.510
to the difference between
the depths of the last Ice

00:05:53.510 --> 00:05:56.690
Age and today.

00:05:56.690 --> 00:05:59.690
And we know all this with
significant confidence.

00:05:59.690 --> 00:06:03.170
In fact, most of the scientific
unknowns-- most, but not all--

00:06:03.170 --> 00:06:04.940
cut the wrong way.

00:06:04.940 --> 00:06:06.740
Do we have less time?

00:06:06.740 --> 00:06:08.900
Are we underestimating
the important feedbacks

00:06:08.900 --> 00:06:10.070
or tipping points?

00:06:10.070 --> 00:06:15.650
And might it be more severe
than we've thought up to now?

00:06:15.650 --> 00:06:18.230
The report also assessed
what social and technological

00:06:18.230 --> 00:06:21.710
transitions would be needed to
avoid these severe outcomes,

00:06:21.710 --> 00:06:26.730
and asserts that a
window is open just

00:06:26.730 --> 00:06:28.830
to keep warming to
roughly 1 and 1/2 degrees

00:06:28.830 --> 00:06:30.960
above pre-industrial levels.

00:06:30.960 --> 00:06:33.690
In a way, that is good news--

00:06:33.690 --> 00:06:34.930
in a way.

00:06:34.930 --> 00:06:38.430
But the sobering message is also
that radical transformations

00:06:38.430 --> 00:06:41.190
need to happen in our
energy and social systems

00:06:41.190 --> 00:06:44.074
on a very, very short timeline.

00:06:46.920 --> 00:06:50.880
That timeline is
about a dozen years.

00:06:50.880 --> 00:06:53.970
By 2030, 12 years
from now, we need

00:06:53.970 --> 00:06:57.540
to have reduced global CO2
emissions by roughly 60%

00:06:57.540 --> 00:07:00.570
from today's levels,
and to reach roughly

00:07:00.570 --> 00:07:06.990
zero net carbon emissions by
2050, or 32 years from today.

00:07:06.990 --> 00:07:09.770
And while that transition
is already underway,

00:07:09.770 --> 00:07:11.400
I'm reminded of the
Marie Curie quote

00:07:11.400 --> 00:07:13.230
about we don't look
at what's behind us.

00:07:13.230 --> 00:07:14.896
We always look at
what's in front of us.

00:07:14.896 --> 00:07:17.400
We are already on
the transition path.

00:07:17.400 --> 00:07:18.630
That transition is happening.

00:07:18.630 --> 00:07:20.490
And I'll return to that later.

00:07:20.490 --> 00:07:22.380
But nevertheless, it
needs to accelerate

00:07:22.380 --> 00:07:26.700
at an unprecedented scale and
pace from where we are today.

00:07:26.700 --> 00:07:29.630
So that brings up this
undiscovered question,

00:07:29.630 --> 00:07:30.680
of can we do it?

00:07:35.276 --> 00:07:36.650
First, let's get
a sense for what

00:07:36.650 --> 00:07:38.270
that scale and
pace of reductions

00:07:38.270 --> 00:07:39.320
really might look like.

00:07:39.320 --> 00:07:42.710
The left figure here is
actually from that IPCC report.

00:07:42.710 --> 00:07:45.740
It's a schematic diagram,
which is sort of cartoonish.

00:07:45.740 --> 00:07:49.340
But what you see on the
left is from roughly 1970

00:07:49.340 --> 00:07:52.850
to 2020, the path of current
global emissions, followed

00:07:52.850 --> 00:07:56.060
by two simplified pathways to
reaching zero net emissions

00:07:56.060 --> 00:07:59.630
by mid-century, which is, again,
what we know we'll need to do.

00:07:59.630 --> 00:08:01.280
The rapidity of
those changes should

00:08:01.280 --> 00:08:04.610
be obvious from just
looking at the chart.

00:08:04.610 --> 00:08:07.490
The table on the right
provides some rough guidelines,

00:08:07.490 --> 00:08:09.950
or some rough estimates,
for the degree of change

00:08:09.950 --> 00:08:14.770
we need to see between
now and 2030 and 2050.

00:08:14.770 --> 00:08:16.270
Take coal, for example--

00:08:16.270 --> 00:08:20.320
coal use needs to decrease
by roughly 60% to 80%

00:08:20.320 --> 00:08:27.620
by 2030, and by
nearly 100% by 2050.

00:08:27.620 --> 00:08:29.360
We need roughly
60% of electricity

00:08:29.360 --> 00:08:32.422
to come from renewables by 2030.

00:08:32.422 --> 00:08:34.130
And in some scenarios,
we would need well

00:08:34.130 --> 00:08:36.409
in excess of 500
billion tons of CO2

00:08:36.409 --> 00:08:38.030
to be captured and
stored underground

00:08:38.030 --> 00:08:41.720
between now and 2100, using
a technology that has not yet

00:08:41.720 --> 00:08:44.560
been deployed at
any kind of scale.

00:08:44.560 --> 00:08:46.060
So clearly, we're
talking at nothing

00:08:46.060 --> 00:08:48.460
less than complete
shutdown of the fossil fuel

00:08:48.460 --> 00:08:54.390
system in the world's economy
over the next roughly 30 years.

00:08:54.390 --> 00:08:56.140
It is a daunting task.

00:08:56.140 --> 00:08:59.820
But like any task, we can take
some steps to ask what we know

00:08:59.820 --> 00:09:02.190
and what we don't know about
what that transition might

00:09:02.190 --> 00:09:04.040
look like.

00:09:04.040 --> 00:09:06.770
So we do have some idea
of what needs to happen

00:09:06.770 --> 00:09:08.614
and what that might look like.

00:09:08.614 --> 00:09:10.030
It turns out that
such transitions

00:09:10.030 --> 00:09:13.330
have been studied for decades
now by modelers, policymakers,

00:09:13.330 --> 00:09:16.700
scientists, technology
experts, and many others.

00:09:16.700 --> 00:09:18.400
And there are a few
consistent features

00:09:18.400 --> 00:09:21.670
across almost all scenarios
that keep climate change

00:09:21.670 --> 00:09:23.380
to minimum levels.

00:09:23.380 --> 00:09:26.530
So first, you can see
here on energy system,

00:09:26.530 --> 00:09:28.090
you use less energy.

00:09:28.090 --> 00:09:29.570
That's energy efficiency.

00:09:29.570 --> 00:09:31.690
That's a core pillar
of what we need to do,

00:09:31.690 --> 00:09:33.820
so all the technologies
that use less energy

00:09:33.820 --> 00:09:35.920
and use it more
efficiently are core

00:09:35.920 --> 00:09:38.510
and central to this
particular one.

00:09:38.510 --> 00:09:40.150
The second piece
is you decarbonize

00:09:40.150 --> 00:09:41.380
all of our electricity.

00:09:41.380 --> 00:09:44.320
In other words, take all of the
electricity we generate now,

00:09:44.320 --> 00:09:47.060
and make it from renewable or
clean sources of some kind--

00:09:47.060 --> 00:09:49.300
no carbon-emitting sources.

00:09:49.300 --> 00:09:51.670
And then finally, you
look at anything possible

00:09:51.670 --> 00:09:53.620
that you can use
electricity to do,

00:09:53.620 --> 00:09:55.870
and you switch over from
fossil fuels to electricity

00:09:55.870 --> 00:09:57.890
for all those applications.

00:09:57.890 --> 00:10:00.010
So those are the pillars
on the energy side.

00:10:00.010 --> 00:10:01.510
And then there's a
few other things.

00:10:01.510 --> 00:10:04.030
You have to think about how to
absorb carbon in land sinks.

00:10:04.030 --> 00:10:07.870
And to some degree, oceans
might be part of this, as well.

00:10:07.870 --> 00:10:10.690
You have to think about
carbon removal technologies,

00:10:10.690 --> 00:10:13.840
maybe in other words, negative
emissions from the atmosphere,

00:10:13.840 --> 00:10:17.352
removing them using energy, and
sequestering them underground.

00:10:17.352 --> 00:10:19.810
And then thinking-- and this
is where some creativity comes

00:10:19.810 --> 00:10:20.470
in--

00:10:20.470 --> 00:10:22.990
thinking about where we
can make substitutions.

00:10:22.990 --> 00:10:25.840
What can we do differently
about how we organize our lives

00:10:25.840 --> 00:10:28.720
and our societies
that can change

00:10:28.720 --> 00:10:31.480
the practices from one sort
of technological strategy

00:10:31.480 --> 00:10:32.800
to another?

00:10:32.800 --> 00:10:37.570
And this I actually was
inspired by the keynote speech

00:10:37.570 --> 00:10:40.000
there, where we heard
about the debacle,

00:10:40.000 --> 00:10:42.130
the breaking up,
where you break it up.

00:10:42.130 --> 00:10:43.810
And you reorganize
the pieces, and you

00:10:43.810 --> 00:10:45.393
think about things
that are different.

00:10:45.393 --> 00:10:48.160
So I'll return to
that in a later slide.

00:10:51.750 --> 00:10:54.584
So we do have an idea
of what needs to happen.

00:10:54.584 --> 00:10:57.000
These are some characteristics
about the coming transition

00:10:57.000 --> 00:10:59.160
that we are pretty
confident about.

00:10:59.160 --> 00:11:01.530
What we're not sure about
is how we operationalize

00:11:01.530 --> 00:11:03.990
the rapid pace of
reductions with what

00:11:03.990 --> 00:11:06.330
I would call the gummy,
imperfect, and sometimes

00:11:06.330 --> 00:11:09.450
intractable social
systems that we have.

00:11:09.450 --> 00:11:11.370
In, part, some of
that's unknowable.

00:11:11.370 --> 00:11:14.460
But in part, we can look
to some other examples

00:11:14.460 --> 00:11:16.960
to give us some ideas.

00:11:16.960 --> 00:11:20.430
So I'll review some perspectives
on transitions of the past,

00:11:20.430 --> 00:11:22.020
and what we know
about the transition

00:11:22.020 --> 00:11:26.070
that we might need to undertake,
to see if we can eliminate both

00:11:26.070 --> 00:11:28.950
what might be possible, and then
how we might organize ourselves

00:11:28.950 --> 00:11:29.890
to go about doing it.

00:11:29.890 --> 00:11:32.430
So I'm going to say four
different points on this.

00:11:32.430 --> 00:11:36.210
So first, there have been rapid
transitions in technologies

00:11:36.210 --> 00:11:37.650
before.

00:11:37.650 --> 00:11:41.250
So we all understand the
concept of it used to be,

00:11:41.250 --> 00:11:43.950
generally horse and
carriage, and we're now

00:11:43.950 --> 00:11:44.700
using automobiles.

00:11:44.700 --> 00:11:48.394
So transition in technologies
is a fundamental issue.

00:11:48.394 --> 00:11:50.310
And we know that those
transitions happen more

00:11:50.310 --> 00:11:52.530
quickly, or can happen quickly.

00:11:52.530 --> 00:11:54.540
This particular
figure shows a number

00:11:54.540 --> 00:11:57.060
of different technological
transitions in the United

00:11:57.060 --> 00:12:02.759
States from 1880 all
the way up to 2010.

00:12:02.759 --> 00:12:04.800
And you don't need to
spend a lot of time looking

00:12:04.800 --> 00:12:07.200
at each individual curve,
but the concept here

00:12:07.200 --> 00:12:09.575
is that this shows a curve
showing early adopters, all

00:12:09.575 --> 00:12:10.950
the way up to kind
of essentially

00:12:10.950 --> 00:12:13.110
full deployment
in the US economy,

00:12:13.110 --> 00:12:14.370
by percentage of households.

00:12:14.370 --> 00:12:16.620
And you can see on the left
side, you have telephones,

00:12:16.620 --> 00:12:17.640
electricity.

00:12:17.640 --> 00:12:20.070
On the right side, you
have things like cell phone

00:12:20.070 --> 00:12:21.520
and the internet.

00:12:21.520 --> 00:12:23.490
So what we're
seeing, first of all,

00:12:23.490 --> 00:12:25.450
is that technologies
do transition.

00:12:25.450 --> 00:12:27.450
And the question is, can
we make that transition

00:12:27.450 --> 00:12:28.870
happen more quickly?

00:12:28.870 --> 00:12:30.220
So let me ask a question.

00:12:30.220 --> 00:12:34.900
How many of you in this
room own a smartphone?

00:12:34.900 --> 00:12:38.030
OK, I should ask how
many don't, but OK.

00:12:38.030 --> 00:12:43.220
So the point is, how many of
you remember that in June 2007,

00:12:43.220 --> 00:12:48.122
there was no such thing
as an app or an iPhone?

00:12:48.122 --> 00:12:48.622
OK.

00:12:52.490 --> 00:12:54.380
And this is where we are today.

00:12:54.380 --> 00:12:58.100
So that's a familiar
example to many of you.

00:12:58.100 --> 00:13:00.290
Roughly 66% of
people in the US now

00:13:00.290 --> 00:13:04.150
own a smartphone, 36%
of people globally.

00:13:04.150 --> 00:13:06.315
Here's another
example-- automobiles,

00:13:06.315 --> 00:13:07.720
I mentioned before.

00:13:07.720 --> 00:13:10.870
Here's a picture of New
York, Fifth Avenue in 1900.

00:13:10.870 --> 00:13:12.790
If you see, there's
a little red circle

00:13:12.790 --> 00:13:17.170
around the single automobile
on the street at that time.

00:13:17.170 --> 00:13:19.790
All the rest are
horse-drawn carriages.

00:13:19.790 --> 00:13:24.250
13 years later, this is the
same scene, to the day--

00:13:24.250 --> 00:13:26.680
essentially 100%
penetration of automobiles

00:13:26.680 --> 00:13:29.274
in that particular
part of the world.

00:13:29.274 --> 00:13:30.690
Now, that's one
part of the world.

00:13:30.690 --> 00:13:32.610
It's not indicative
of the whole country.

00:13:32.610 --> 00:13:35.310
For the whole country, it
went from roughly 1% in 1900

00:13:35.310 --> 00:13:40.140
to 99% automobiles by 1930.

00:13:40.140 --> 00:13:42.140
And this happens across
a lot of different kinds

00:13:42.140 --> 00:13:42.850
of technologies.

00:13:42.850 --> 00:13:44.558
There have been rapid
transitions before.

00:13:44.558 --> 00:13:46.302
One you might not
be familiar with,

00:13:46.302 --> 00:13:48.260
because it happened in
Brazil, was a transition

00:13:48.260 --> 00:13:50.060
from traditional
vehicles to vehicles

00:13:50.060 --> 00:13:52.490
that can use either
ethanol or gasoline, called

00:13:52.490 --> 00:13:53.840
flex-fuel vehicles.

00:13:53.840 --> 00:13:57.290
That particular transition
happened in the 2000s--

00:13:57.290 --> 00:14:03.480
roughly 5% of sales in 2003
to over 90% of sales in 2009--

00:14:03.480 --> 00:14:05.330
five years to kind
of essentially almost

00:14:05.330 --> 00:14:08.799
full deployment on
the sales front.

00:14:08.799 --> 00:14:11.090
So the point there is that
we can see rapid transitions

00:14:11.090 --> 00:14:12.170
in technologies.

00:14:12.170 --> 00:14:14.070
I should caveat-- these
are all contingent.

00:14:14.070 --> 00:14:16.340
They're all specific to
the local circumstances.

00:14:16.340 --> 00:14:19.694
They have a lot of
contingencies as to whether they

00:14:19.694 --> 00:14:20.360
can work or not.

00:14:20.360 --> 00:14:23.540
We have to think about how
those really worked in practice,

00:14:23.540 --> 00:14:25.770
and think about how we can
apply it into the future.

00:14:25.770 --> 00:14:27.950
I'm not saying it's just
going to magically happen.

00:14:27.950 --> 00:14:29.640
Second on the
transition perspectives,

00:14:29.640 --> 00:14:32.540
we have had broad
mobilization before.

00:14:32.540 --> 00:14:36.124
And in fact, that IPCC report
calls out one specific example,

00:14:36.124 --> 00:14:37.790
which many of you
were probably thinking

00:14:37.790 --> 00:14:40.010
about when I use the
term "mobilization,"

00:14:40.010 --> 00:14:42.790
which is World War II.

00:14:42.790 --> 00:14:45.580
So in World War II,
defense expenditure

00:14:45.580 --> 00:14:49.120
rose from roughly $2
billion in 1940 to $91

00:14:49.120 --> 00:14:50.200
billion four years later.

00:14:50.200 --> 00:14:54.610
That increase is equivalent to
$1 trillion in current dollars,

00:14:54.610 --> 00:14:55.820
in four years.

00:14:55.820 --> 00:14:58.090
The US produced about 40%
of the world's armaments

00:14:58.090 --> 00:15:01.060
over that time, including
300,000 airplanes, 100,000

00:15:01.060 --> 00:15:03.750
ships, and much, much more.

00:15:03.750 --> 00:15:06.270
And we increased our
workforce by 7.7,

00:15:06.270 --> 00:15:07.859
almost 8 million people.

00:15:07.859 --> 00:15:09.900
People that hadn't been
in the civilian workforce

00:15:09.900 --> 00:15:11.910
before had entered the
civilian workforce.

00:15:11.910 --> 00:15:13.284
And you can see
an example of one

00:15:13.284 --> 00:15:16.080
of those people in
the poster here--

00:15:16.080 --> 00:15:18.090
obviously, an icon for
the fact that women

00:15:18.090 --> 00:15:21.125
were moving much more
broadly into the workforce.

00:15:21.125 --> 00:15:22.000
So that's an example.

00:15:22.000 --> 00:15:25.304
It's called out even
by the IPCC report.

00:15:25.304 --> 00:15:27.220
We know that happened
in one specific country,

00:15:27.220 --> 00:15:29.590
under one specific
set of circumstances.

00:15:29.590 --> 00:15:31.600
We know that that
level of mobilization

00:15:31.600 --> 00:15:34.210
will likely have to happen
over the next 15 years.

00:15:34.210 --> 00:15:37.840
So the real question
is, how can we do that?

00:15:37.840 --> 00:15:41.140
How can we make that
happen on a global scale?

00:15:41.140 --> 00:15:43.780
The third perspective
I want to share on this

00:15:43.780 --> 00:15:46.880
is tying back to
the theme of today,

00:15:46.880 --> 00:15:51.060
which is that our thinking
has often been wrong.

00:15:51.060 --> 00:15:55.140
And we learn from it, but
it has often been wrong.

00:15:55.140 --> 00:15:56.640
I'm going to give
just two examples,

00:15:56.640 --> 00:15:57.930
although there are many.

00:15:57.930 --> 00:15:58.920
There are many here.

00:15:58.920 --> 00:16:00.730
Think back to the 1970s.

00:16:00.730 --> 00:16:03.000
The middle of the 1970s,
there was an oil crisis.

00:16:03.000 --> 00:16:05.208
There were a lot of smart
people trying to figure out

00:16:05.208 --> 00:16:07.590
what energy demand would look
like in the United States,

00:16:07.590 --> 00:16:09.390
to try to plan for it.

00:16:09.390 --> 00:16:11.820
This figure shows a number
of different forecasts

00:16:11.820 --> 00:16:13.937
from that period
of energy demand.

00:16:13.937 --> 00:16:15.520
I don't know if you
can see the scale.

00:16:15.520 --> 00:16:19.440
It's 1975 to 2000 was
the projection period.

00:16:19.440 --> 00:16:22.380
And like I said, a lot of the
smartest people, so we think,

00:16:22.380 --> 00:16:24.224
were doing these projections.

00:16:24.224 --> 00:16:25.640
So if you are
looking at this, you

00:16:25.640 --> 00:16:29.700
might say, well, OK, probably
somewhere in the middle.

00:16:29.700 --> 00:16:31.947
What the actual
amount of demand was,

00:16:31.947 --> 00:16:33.780
was at the very bottom
end of that envelope.

00:16:33.780 --> 00:16:36.810
In other words, the economy
did much better on efficiency

00:16:36.810 --> 00:16:38.760
than people had anticipated.

00:16:38.760 --> 00:16:41.735
So people, in aggregate,
were quite wrong about where

00:16:41.735 --> 00:16:42.360
we were headed.

00:16:42.360 --> 00:16:43.260
And they were wrong--

00:16:43.260 --> 00:16:45.510
in some way, we kind
of came out better

00:16:45.510 --> 00:16:48.772
than people thought
at that point.

00:16:48.772 --> 00:16:49.730
Here's another example.

00:16:49.730 --> 00:16:51.344
This one's a little
harder to follow.

00:16:51.344 --> 00:16:52.760
But what I want
you to see here is

00:16:52.760 --> 00:16:54.530
that this is a set
of solar forecasts

00:16:54.530 --> 00:16:56.150
over a period of
roughly 10 years

00:16:56.150 --> 00:16:59.390
from a single organization, the
International Energy Agency.

00:16:59.390 --> 00:17:01.250
Of course, we presume
that people would--

00:17:01.250 --> 00:17:03.107
we're certainly much
smarter now, of course.

00:17:03.107 --> 00:17:04.940
We have better models,
and all these things.

00:17:04.940 --> 00:17:06.950
We've learned from our mistakes.

00:17:06.950 --> 00:17:09.410
But what this shows is
that we actually didn't.

00:17:09.410 --> 00:17:11.780
Each of those colored
bars shows a forecast

00:17:11.780 --> 00:17:13.849
from a subsequent year.

00:17:13.849 --> 00:17:16.550
So the forecast started
out very low for what

00:17:16.550 --> 00:17:17.839
solar would look like.

00:17:17.839 --> 00:17:19.700
And they increasingly
got higher.

00:17:19.700 --> 00:17:21.829
And if you see the
dotted line there,

00:17:21.829 --> 00:17:24.349
the dotted line at the very
upper end of that envelope

00:17:24.349 --> 00:17:27.200
is where solar deployment
actually happened.

00:17:27.200 --> 00:17:30.440
So the solar deployment
was way faster, way faster

00:17:30.440 --> 00:17:33.470
than the International
Energy Agency predicted.

00:17:33.470 --> 00:17:36.800
So each of these years
the forecasts increased.

00:17:36.800 --> 00:17:39.500
And they were always lagging
by a significant amount

00:17:39.500 --> 00:17:41.910
from where reality really was--

00:17:41.910 --> 00:17:46.630
so very far behind in terms of
thinking about solar deployment

00:17:46.630 --> 00:17:47.360
globally.

00:17:47.360 --> 00:17:48.860
And by the way,
it's not just IEA.

00:17:48.860 --> 00:17:50.193
There have been studies of this.

00:17:50.193 --> 00:17:52.400
There's been lots of
other organizations made

00:17:52.400 --> 00:17:54.035
the same error in judgment.

00:17:54.035 --> 00:17:56.660
So the point there is that when
we think about the future, when

00:17:56.660 --> 00:17:59.000
we think about what's
possible, we often

00:17:59.000 --> 00:18:01.460
think about kind of
drawing extrapolations

00:18:01.460 --> 00:18:03.980
from where we were
today, and not

00:18:03.980 --> 00:18:07.472
thinking about what can happen
under different circumstances.

00:18:07.472 --> 00:18:09.680
This has happened in energy
demand, as I just showed.

00:18:09.680 --> 00:18:10.910
It's happened in eVs.

00:18:10.910 --> 00:18:12.320
It's happened in photovoltaics.

00:18:12.320 --> 00:18:14.840
It's happened in wind, and
it's happened in batteries,

00:18:14.840 --> 00:18:18.070
among many others, that
we've been surprised

00:18:18.070 --> 00:18:21.100
by the rate of change, even
with smart people thinking

00:18:21.100 --> 00:18:23.944
about where it might
actually end up.

00:18:23.944 --> 00:18:25.360
The fourth piece
I want to mention

00:18:25.360 --> 00:18:27.340
is that we are
actually, right now,

00:18:27.340 --> 00:18:30.040
in the middle of a
revolution in clean energy.

00:18:30.040 --> 00:18:31.442
We need to be aware of that.

00:18:31.442 --> 00:18:33.400
We need to acknowledge
that's what's happening,

00:18:33.400 --> 00:18:36.210
and be open to that.

00:18:36.210 --> 00:18:38.797
I use the word
"revolution" not fliply.

00:18:38.797 --> 00:18:40.380
I think it's actually
really important

00:18:40.380 --> 00:18:43.170
that we're considering what
the implications of that are.

00:18:43.170 --> 00:18:45.450
But it actually is happening.

00:18:45.450 --> 00:18:47.850
Currently, onshore wind or
traditional wind turbines

00:18:47.850 --> 00:18:50.430
are one of the most competitive
sources for new generation,

00:18:50.430 --> 00:18:52.560
coming in at roughly
$0.03 a kilowatt-hour.

00:18:52.560 --> 00:18:56.550
That's at the very low end
of what fossil can generate.

00:18:56.550 --> 00:18:58.920
Solar photovoltaic, as I
mentioned in the earlier slide,

00:18:58.920 --> 00:19:01.800
has been quite surprising
over the last decade.

00:19:01.800 --> 00:19:04.500
The figure here shows
a longer term decrease

00:19:04.500 --> 00:19:08.400
from 1975 to 2007 in
the orange on price,

00:19:08.400 --> 00:19:10.560
and a corresponding
dramatic increase

00:19:10.560 --> 00:19:15.020
of photovoltaic deployment on
the right in the bluish color.

00:19:15.020 --> 00:19:20.630
Costs have fallen 73%, roughly
80% over the last decade.

00:19:20.630 --> 00:19:22.430
Over the last six
years, more money

00:19:22.430 --> 00:19:24.920
was invested in renewable
energy than has been invested

00:19:24.920 --> 00:19:26.850
in new fossil generation.

00:19:26.850 --> 00:19:28.760
So that's a significant outcome.

00:19:28.760 --> 00:19:32.090
$280 billion last year
was invested in renewables

00:19:32.090 --> 00:19:34.070
globally, outstripping
the amount

00:19:34.070 --> 00:19:38.510
we spent on all fossil
generation investments.

00:19:38.510 --> 00:19:40.880
And finally, the international
Renewable Energy Agency

00:19:40.880 --> 00:19:43.610
does estimate, with all the
cost drops we're seeing,

00:19:43.610 --> 00:19:45.380
that renewable energy
will consistently

00:19:45.380 --> 00:19:47.330
be cheaper than
most fossil fuels

00:19:47.330 --> 00:19:51.230
in every part of
the world by 2020.

00:19:51.230 --> 00:19:55.010
So for new generation,
we have the opportunities

00:19:55.010 --> 00:19:57.350
to deploy these new
kinds of technologies

00:19:57.350 --> 00:20:01.310
without radical
thinking about, will we

00:20:01.310 --> 00:20:05.120
have to pay tons more somehow,
in order to have this happen?

00:20:05.120 --> 00:20:07.850
Now there are other
challenges technically

00:20:07.850 --> 00:20:10.776
about deploying renewables at
fast scale and at rapid rates.

00:20:10.776 --> 00:20:12.650
I don't want to minimize
those, but the point

00:20:12.650 --> 00:20:15.920
is that we have the tools
right now at our disposal

00:20:15.920 --> 00:20:17.968
to do a rapid deployment.

00:20:20.600 --> 00:20:25.190
So those are some
observations from the past,

00:20:25.190 --> 00:20:27.470
from the present,
about some perspectives

00:20:27.470 --> 00:20:29.630
on what this transition
might look like.

00:20:29.630 --> 00:20:31.040
But there are
still some elements

00:20:31.040 --> 00:20:34.006
that we still don't
know what to do.

00:20:34.006 --> 00:20:35.380
We don't know how
to go about it.

00:20:35.380 --> 00:20:37.070
And I think we have to
be honest with ourselves

00:20:37.070 --> 00:20:39.319
that we need to be thinking
creatively and differently

00:20:39.319 --> 00:20:41.000
about some of this stuff.

00:20:41.000 --> 00:20:44.030
The IPCC report that I
mentioned earlier does mention

00:20:44.030 --> 00:20:46.760
that the rates of changes
that we do need to see

00:20:46.760 --> 00:20:47.940
have occurred in the past.

00:20:47.940 --> 00:20:50.120
So that's what I was
essentially reflecting to you,

00:20:50.120 --> 00:20:52.970
within specific sectors,
within specific technologies,

00:20:52.970 --> 00:20:54.950
within specific spatial context.

00:20:54.950 --> 00:20:58.070
But there is no documented
historical precedent

00:20:58.070 --> 00:20:59.427
for their scale.

00:20:59.427 --> 00:21:01.760
So it's the scaling question
and the social organization

00:21:01.760 --> 00:21:03.500
question that really
is at the heart

00:21:03.500 --> 00:21:07.470
of this particular problem.

00:21:07.470 --> 00:21:11.490
So this problem, I want to split
up into a couple of components.

00:21:11.490 --> 00:21:13.710
In one of the earlier talks,
we heard about the fact

00:21:13.710 --> 00:21:15.690
that there's individual
components of a system,

00:21:15.690 --> 00:21:17.512
and then there's
a system thinking.

00:21:17.512 --> 00:21:19.470
Part of the individual
components of our system

00:21:19.470 --> 00:21:20.970
will, of course,
be the technologies

00:21:20.970 --> 00:21:23.250
that we use to deliver
the services we need.

00:21:23.250 --> 00:21:26.130
And we know that there
are many such technologies

00:21:26.130 --> 00:21:27.660
at our fingertips right now.

00:21:27.660 --> 00:21:30.460
Many of you will recognize a
number of electric vehicles.

00:21:30.460 --> 00:21:33.130
These are existing
electric vehicles today.

00:21:33.130 --> 00:21:35.730
We have batteries that we
can deploy, battery storage.

00:21:35.730 --> 00:21:37.290
We have drone delivery.

00:21:37.290 --> 00:21:40.930
Very importantly, we have drone
delivery of Domino's pizzas,

00:21:40.930 --> 00:21:42.810
which is shown here.

00:21:42.810 --> 00:21:45.630
We have autonomous vehicles,
which are increasingly

00:21:45.630 --> 00:21:48.330
being tested and
deployed, and will likely

00:21:48.330 --> 00:21:51.480
be deployed at scale and in
the relatively near term.

00:21:51.480 --> 00:21:53.275
We have offshore wind turbines.

00:21:53.275 --> 00:21:54.900
Some of them are
anchored, some of them

00:21:54.900 --> 00:21:57.450
are not, but increasingly
deployed globally.

00:21:57.450 --> 00:21:58.894
We have magnetic
levitation trains

00:21:58.894 --> 00:22:00.060
that have been demonstrated.

00:22:00.060 --> 00:22:01.920
We have carbon capture
and sequestration,

00:22:01.920 --> 00:22:04.080
which has been demonstrated
and commercialized.

00:22:04.080 --> 00:22:08.310
And we even have-- and this is
one of the more different kinds

00:22:08.310 --> 00:22:10.020
of technologies you
might think of--

00:22:10.020 --> 00:22:13.020
meatless burgers,
which could, in fact,

00:22:13.020 --> 00:22:17.040
be a significant contributor to
the change in carbon emissions

00:22:17.040 --> 00:22:19.910
from our agricultural sector.

00:22:19.910 --> 00:22:21.294
We also have technologies that--

00:22:21.294 --> 00:22:22.960
there's not a bright
line between these,

00:22:22.960 --> 00:22:24.882
but that kind of are
concept technologies.

00:22:24.882 --> 00:22:26.590
We have technologies
that we can actually

00:22:26.590 --> 00:22:29.410
use to suck CO2 out
of the atmosphere

00:22:29.410 --> 00:22:32.470
and sequester it in the
ground or in solid materials.

00:22:32.470 --> 00:22:34.900
We have Elon Musk's Hyperloop,
which I'm sure some of you

00:22:34.900 --> 00:22:36.220
have read about.

00:22:36.220 --> 00:22:38.650
We have small, modular
nuclear reactors,

00:22:38.650 --> 00:22:41.290
which might be
proliferation-resistant ways

00:22:41.290 --> 00:22:43.490
to get low-carbon energy.

00:22:43.490 --> 00:22:47.550
We also have the ever possible
option of nuclear fusion, which

00:22:47.550 --> 00:22:49.330
people continue to
work on, and may well

00:22:49.330 --> 00:22:52.390
come through one of
these days, but is not--

00:22:52.390 --> 00:22:53.560
it could happen.

00:22:53.560 --> 00:22:59.140
And then finally, we have our
familiar unknown unknowns.

00:22:59.140 --> 00:23:01.046
So in technology,
as you all know,

00:23:01.046 --> 00:23:02.170
there's always discoveries.

00:23:02.170 --> 00:23:03.730
We're always finding new things.

00:23:03.730 --> 00:23:05.530
Many of those things
are hard to predict

00:23:05.530 --> 00:23:08.500
from where we stand today, that
may still make a big difference

00:23:08.500 --> 00:23:10.540
in, say, 2030 or 2040.

00:23:10.540 --> 00:23:12.820
And that's one area
where many of you,

00:23:12.820 --> 00:23:15.910
particularly I'm looking at the
young people in the audience,

00:23:15.910 --> 00:23:18.550
might be able, with your
scientific inquiries

00:23:18.550 --> 00:23:20.740
or scientific interests
or technological skills

00:23:20.740 --> 00:23:23.290
that you're building right
now, be able to kind of grab

00:23:23.290 --> 00:23:25.360
on to some idea
that you might have,

00:23:25.360 --> 00:23:27.610
and make that into
a reality that

00:23:27.610 --> 00:23:30.619
really does help the world.

00:23:30.619 --> 00:23:32.660
But like I said, it is
not just the technologies.

00:23:32.660 --> 00:23:34.290
The technologies are
a piece of the puzzle,

00:23:34.290 --> 00:23:35.190
but they're not the system.

00:23:35.190 --> 00:23:37.670
So we have to think about the
broader systemic approaches

00:23:37.670 --> 00:23:41.180
that we can take,
reorganizing ourselves.

00:23:41.180 --> 00:23:43.910
Reorganizing ourselves--
that mobilization

00:23:43.910 --> 00:23:46.280
which includes technology,
but also includes

00:23:46.280 --> 00:23:50.870
organizations, governance,
personal choices, and more.

00:23:50.870 --> 00:23:52.710
And this is where we
have to be creative.

00:23:52.710 --> 00:23:56.850
And this is, in some ways,
where it is somewhat unknown.

00:23:56.850 --> 00:23:59.584
This is a diagrammatic depiction
of blockchain, which some

00:23:59.584 --> 00:24:00.750
of you may be familiar with.

00:24:00.750 --> 00:24:02.900
But people have talked
about blockchain as a way

00:24:02.900 --> 00:24:07.610
that we can essentially use
distributed energy sources

00:24:07.610 --> 00:24:10.820
and distributed storage within
the context of a smart grid,

00:24:10.820 --> 00:24:13.029
which is the diagram
on the right,

00:24:13.029 --> 00:24:15.320
to actually build out these
technologies on a much more

00:24:15.320 --> 00:24:20.470
rapid pace, and allow people
to get paid for it as they go.

00:24:20.470 --> 00:24:22.720
There's also food waste as
another way to think about.

00:24:22.720 --> 00:24:24.303
Some people have
worked on food waste.

00:24:24.303 --> 00:24:26.110
Food waste actually
accounts-- something

00:24:26.110 --> 00:24:28.401
like a third of the food
that's produced globally today

00:24:28.401 --> 00:24:29.020
is wasted.

00:24:29.020 --> 00:24:32.710
It counts for something like 5%
to 7% of global GHG emissions

00:24:32.710 --> 00:24:33.910
just from the waste.

00:24:33.910 --> 00:24:36.820
So if there's a way that we
can reuse the food that we were

00:24:36.820 --> 00:24:39.530
already throwing away,
or use less of it,

00:24:39.530 --> 00:24:41.320
those kinds of
approaches are going

00:24:41.320 --> 00:24:42.890
to be essentially important.

00:24:42.890 --> 00:24:45.015
And then finally, one that's
probably more familiar

00:24:45.015 --> 00:24:47.110
is retooling and rethinking
how we do our work,

00:24:47.110 --> 00:24:49.720
and how we do our transportation
and living situations.

00:24:49.720 --> 00:24:50.560
So can we telework?

00:24:50.560 --> 00:24:54.160
Can we do other modes of
engaging with our workplaces,

00:24:54.160 --> 00:24:58.390
but also with each other, that
ideally are more personally

00:24:58.390 --> 00:25:01.760
fulfilling, less greenhouse
gas emissions, and also,

00:25:01.760 --> 00:25:03.590
maybe, better for our health?

00:25:03.590 --> 00:25:08.065
So we can track that
with the health tracker.

00:25:08.065 --> 00:25:10.440
One example that I want to
give on organizing strategies,

00:25:10.440 --> 00:25:13.924
we are now running an
experiment in the United States.

00:25:13.924 --> 00:25:15.340
A year and a half
ago Donald Trump

00:25:15.340 --> 00:25:17.020
announced his intent to
pull out of the Paris

00:25:17.020 --> 00:25:18.186
Agreement on Climate Change.

00:25:18.186 --> 00:25:20.440
Some of you may have heard
that when it happened.

00:25:20.440 --> 00:25:23.650
Within 72 hours of that
announcement, a coalition

00:25:23.650 --> 00:25:26.830
of 2,700 cities, states and
businesses stepped up to say,

00:25:26.830 --> 00:25:27.670
we are still in.

00:25:27.670 --> 00:25:30.599
We are still committed to the
goals of the Paris Agreement.

00:25:30.599 --> 00:25:32.140
That group is called
We Are Still In.

00:25:32.140 --> 00:25:33.160
And they've been
working with a group

00:25:33.160 --> 00:25:35.368
that I'm affiliated with
called America's Pledge, led

00:25:35.368 --> 00:25:37.240
by Michael Bloomberg
and Jerry Brown,

00:25:37.240 --> 00:25:39.880
to think about how we can
organize ourselves differently

00:25:39.880 --> 00:25:41.650
at different levels
of governance,

00:25:41.650 --> 00:25:44.050
to accelerate what otherwise
would have happened

00:25:44.050 --> 00:25:45.160
in this country.

00:25:45.160 --> 00:25:48.370
So that coalition, which is
depicted graphically here,

00:25:48.370 --> 00:25:52.120
is now over 3,500 strong.

00:25:52.120 --> 00:25:56.550
It represents over
half the US population,

00:25:56.550 --> 00:26:00.842
and it represents
almost 60% of US GDP.

00:26:00.842 --> 00:26:03.300
So were it a country, it would
be the world's third largest

00:26:03.300 --> 00:26:08.450
economy and the world's fourth
largest greenhouse gas emitter.

00:26:08.450 --> 00:26:10.800
So I'm going to say two more
things about this topic.

00:26:10.800 --> 00:26:13.112
The first one is that we
can choose our future.

00:26:13.112 --> 00:26:14.570
The future that we
have is not just

00:26:14.570 --> 00:26:15.890
sort of pain and suffering.

00:26:15.890 --> 00:26:18.380
It's very much kind
of a positive story

00:26:18.380 --> 00:26:20.150
of benefits and health.

00:26:20.150 --> 00:26:21.650
So first of all,
there's an estimate

00:26:21.650 --> 00:26:23.720
that we could benefit
by $26 trillion dollars

00:26:23.720 --> 00:26:26.080
with this low-carbon investment.

00:26:26.080 --> 00:26:28.600
Up to 150 million
premature deaths

00:26:28.600 --> 00:26:31.390
avoided due to
reduced air pollution.

00:26:31.390 --> 00:26:33.460
And finally, subsidy
reform in carbon pricing

00:26:33.460 --> 00:26:35.890
that would put another
roughly $3 trillion

00:26:35.890 --> 00:26:38.020
into government
revenues by 2030,

00:26:38.020 --> 00:26:42.500
which is over the GDP of India.

00:26:42.500 --> 00:26:45.080
So finally, the answer
is, can we do it?

00:26:45.080 --> 00:26:48.760
And the answer is, yes, we
can under four specific kind

00:26:48.760 --> 00:26:50.000
of possibilities.

00:26:50.000 --> 00:26:51.610
First of all, to
improve the odds,

00:26:51.610 --> 00:26:53.680
we have to think about
funding technology, R&amp;D,

00:26:53.680 --> 00:26:56.050
and fostering demand
with the private sector.

00:26:56.050 --> 00:26:58.212
Second, we have to build
this into the economy

00:26:58.212 --> 00:26:59.920
by investing in new
green infrastructure,

00:26:59.920 --> 00:27:02.300
pricing carbon, and
disclosing risk.

00:27:02.300 --> 00:27:04.300
We have to reorganize
ourselves, as I mentioned,

00:27:04.300 --> 00:27:05.950
acting at all levels
of government,

00:27:05.950 --> 00:27:09.220
using governance and policy as
a way to focus our responses.

00:27:09.220 --> 00:27:11.200
And finally-- and this
is where I want to link

00:27:11.200 --> 00:27:13.616
in to the earlier comments
that were made at the front end

00:27:13.616 --> 00:27:14.680
of the session--

00:27:14.680 --> 00:27:16.330
is to embrace our humanity.

00:27:16.330 --> 00:27:17.920
This is a broad
economic opportunity,

00:27:17.920 --> 00:27:20.180
but some people will
have to be displaced.

00:27:20.180 --> 00:27:22.330
And so we have to
think about making sure

00:27:22.330 --> 00:27:24.220
that the politics and
the transition strategy

00:27:24.220 --> 00:27:27.400
works for all people,
and not just some.

00:27:27.400 --> 00:27:30.100
And with that, I will conclude,
and say thanks very much.

00:27:30.100 --> 00:27:31.750
And we can go to questions.

