00:46:26.530 --> 00:46:27.530
in trying to understand.

00:46:27.530 --> 00:46:29.880
So that's an area,
if you're interested,

00:46:29.880 --> 00:46:34.267
is very important
to contribute to.

00:46:34.267 --> 00:46:36.350
But right now, I think
it's important to remember,

00:46:36.350 --> 00:46:39.740
we are actually living
it at the moment.

00:46:39.740 --> 00:46:44.420
There are these events that are
unequivocally, or pretty much

00:46:44.420 --> 00:46:47.120
obviously, driven
by climate change,

00:46:47.120 --> 00:46:49.790
and that those are part of
what we're experiencing now.

00:46:49.790 --> 00:46:52.960
Those were the predictions
that we had 20 years ago--

00:46:52.960 --> 00:46:56.020
the droughts, the floods, the
fires, the intense hurricanes,

00:46:56.020 --> 00:46:56.810
et cetera.

00:46:56.810 --> 00:46:59.550
We are seeing the impacts
of climate change today.

00:46:59.550 --> 00:47:02.090
So it's important
when you're speaking

00:47:02.090 --> 00:47:04.490
with people about that to be
aware that that's actually

00:47:04.490 --> 00:47:05.957
already affecting lives.

00:47:05.957 --> 00:47:08.940
- Thank you.

00:47:08.940 --> 00:47:10.920
- Jo Solid again.

00:47:10.920 --> 00:47:14.340
I would like to turn to this
question that was raised

00:47:14.340 --> 00:47:16.890
about communities of faith.

00:47:16.890 --> 00:47:18.930
It has been explained
to me that there

00:47:18.930 --> 00:47:24.270
are people who see
this potential climate

00:47:24.270 --> 00:47:30.360
change apocalypse
as aligned with what

00:47:30.360 --> 00:47:35.570
the future of humanity
is meant to be by God.

00:47:35.570 --> 00:47:38.540
And they talk about
this as the Rapture--

00:47:38.540 --> 00:47:40.160
that the world will collapse.

00:47:40.160 --> 00:47:43.640
And the worthy will
be sent up to Heaven.

00:47:43.640 --> 00:47:46.670
These folks don't
see a big incentive

00:47:46.670 --> 00:47:48.890
to stopping that from
happening, because they

00:47:48.890 --> 00:47:51.410
see themselves as worthy.

00:47:51.410 --> 00:47:53.720
It's been described,
apparently, as part

00:47:53.720 --> 00:47:56.690
of what goes on in Louisiana,
where you see the oil

00:47:56.690 --> 00:48:00.440
companies destroying the
bayous, and the death

00:48:00.440 --> 00:48:04.400
of the once highly valued
natural environment there.

00:48:04.400 --> 00:48:07.460
And they accept this,
based on their beliefs.

00:48:07.460 --> 00:48:09.750
How do we deal with that?

00:48:09.750 --> 00:48:11.090
- But that's not just Louisiana.

00:48:11.090 --> 00:48:12.390
I mean, this is a--

00:48:15.550 --> 00:48:17.480
lot of different
opinions in Louisiana.

00:48:17.480 --> 00:48:18.830
- I mean, look--

00:48:18.830 --> 00:48:22.280
I actually don't have a great
answer to that one, either.

00:48:22.280 --> 00:48:25.250
There is a point where you do
want to engage with people,

00:48:25.250 --> 00:48:28.610
and be discussing in good faith.

00:48:28.610 --> 00:48:33.740
On the other hand, it's also
possible to make the numbers

00:48:33.740 --> 00:48:38.960
work on our side, so that
ultimately, there might--

00:48:38.960 --> 00:48:40.586
some people might
never be convinced.

00:48:40.586 --> 00:48:41.960
And I think we
have to kind of be

00:48:41.960 --> 00:48:44.300
aware, in our social
systems, that we

00:48:44.300 --> 00:48:46.400
have to continue to
kind of carry them along

00:48:46.400 --> 00:48:48.680
with us, as we're trying
to make these transitions,

00:48:48.680 --> 00:48:53.150
and do so in as empathetic and
constructive way as we can.

00:48:53.150 --> 00:48:55.560
But there is a way in which--

00:48:55.560 --> 00:48:57.170
engagement is good.

00:48:57.170 --> 00:48:59.264
I think there are
people who are very

00:48:59.264 --> 00:49:00.680
much in this
community of thinking

00:49:00.680 --> 00:49:03.870
about the overlap between
ethics, values, faith,

00:49:03.870 --> 00:49:07.970
and our choices in policy,
and environment, and climate.

00:49:07.970 --> 00:49:09.830
And I wish them well.

00:49:09.830 --> 00:49:11.250
It's not something
I directly do.

00:49:11.250 --> 00:49:12.860
But other people do
that very eloquently.

00:49:12.860 --> 00:49:14.655
I think, of, for example
Katharine Hayhoe,

00:49:14.655 --> 00:49:17.720
who's a climate scientist-- and
you might want to look her up--

00:49:17.720 --> 00:49:19.497
does a lot of
engagement like this,

00:49:19.497 --> 00:49:21.830
with different faith communities
and the Christian faith

00:49:21.830 --> 00:49:22.916
communities, particularly.

00:49:22.916 --> 00:49:24.290
So there are people
like that who

00:49:24.290 --> 00:49:26.854
can be advocates, who can
sort of bring the message out.

00:49:26.854 --> 00:49:28.520
And I think the other
part of it is just

00:49:28.520 --> 00:49:32.065
to continue to make that case
that this is a positive future

00:49:32.065 --> 00:49:32.690
we're choosing.

00:49:32.690 --> 00:49:36.890
It's not something
that should necessarily

00:49:36.890 --> 00:49:40.710
lead to a worse outcome for
those people who are perhaps

00:49:40.710 --> 00:49:43.600
not doing anything about it.

00:49:43.600 --> 00:49:45.100
- There are groups
like Evangelicals

00:49:45.100 --> 00:49:47.170
for Climate Action, for
instance, who are increasingly

00:49:47.170 --> 00:49:48.100
finding their voice.

00:49:48.100 --> 00:49:51.520
And I welcome now the last
question in this fabulous set

00:49:51.520 --> 00:49:53.760
of questions.

00:49:53.760 --> 00:49:54.590
- Excuse me.

00:49:54.590 --> 00:49:55.360
Lee Goodman.

00:49:55.360 --> 00:49:58.490
I'm a retired
transportation engineer.

00:49:58.490 --> 00:49:59.390
I like to talk.

00:49:59.390 --> 00:50:01.310
I'm very much in
favor of what we're

00:50:01.310 --> 00:50:02.999
going to do in the future.

00:50:02.999 --> 00:50:04.790
But what can we learn
from the present that

00:50:04.790 --> 00:50:07.400
will help to change attitudes?

00:50:07.400 --> 00:50:09.630
I'd like to know if there's
any research going on,

00:50:09.630 --> 00:50:14.460
or if we're checking into
what's happening in Europe.

00:50:14.460 --> 00:50:17.090
My perception is that there
are many countries in Europe

00:50:17.090 --> 00:50:20.530
which are way ahead of us
in terms of renewable energy

00:50:20.530 --> 00:50:21.030
policies.

00:50:21.030 --> 00:50:24.140
France in particular, I think,
has a tremendous percentage

00:50:24.140 --> 00:50:28.010
of its electricity generated
by nuclear right now.

00:50:28.010 --> 00:50:30.260
Can we learn anything
from them in terms

00:50:30.260 --> 00:50:34.320
of helping to accelerate
the transition?

00:50:34.320 --> 00:50:36.990
- So it's a great point, and I
have two quick answers to that.

00:50:36.990 --> 00:50:38.347
So first is, absolutely yes.

00:50:38.347 --> 00:50:39.680
There are a number of countries.

00:50:39.680 --> 00:50:41.930
There is lots of experiments
going on globally.

00:50:41.930 --> 00:50:44.138
There's been a lot of
leadership from different parts

00:50:44.138 --> 00:50:45.770
of the world in
renewable deployment.

00:50:45.770 --> 00:50:47.829
We are kind of trying
to learn from those.

00:50:47.829 --> 00:50:50.120
I think it's good to kind of
cross-fertilize with ideas

00:50:50.120 --> 00:50:52.880
and policies and approaches that
have worked in other places,

00:50:52.880 --> 00:50:56.030
and also learn from
what the failures were.

00:50:56.030 --> 00:50:57.530
A second dimension
of your question,

00:50:57.530 --> 00:51:01.550
that I think we can potentially
wrap on or leave off on,

00:51:01.550 --> 00:51:03.980
we talked earlier in the
day about the connections

00:51:03.980 --> 00:51:06.599
between some of the work
that's being done in science

00:51:06.599 --> 00:51:09.140
and some work that's being done
in, say, humanities or social

00:51:09.140 --> 00:51:09.860
science.

00:51:09.860 --> 00:51:13.220
We even kicked off today with
some art, with the poetry.

00:51:13.220 --> 00:51:17.030
And I think that this is an area
where making those connections,

00:51:17.030 --> 00:51:19.640
thinking about what those
other disciplines can bring

00:51:19.640 --> 00:51:22.430
to the table to help us
understand how we have

00:51:22.430 --> 00:51:25.460
organized and how we
successfully organize ourselves

00:51:25.460 --> 00:51:29.390
as human systems, as
cultural, social people--

00:51:29.390 --> 00:51:30.672
how do we organize ourselves?

00:51:30.672 --> 00:51:31.880
How do we motivate ourselves?

00:51:31.880 --> 00:51:36.609
How do we kind of collectively
move in a certain direction?

00:51:36.609 --> 00:51:38.900
That's something that a lot
of these other disciplines,

00:51:38.900 --> 00:51:40.520
I think, have a lot to say.

00:51:40.520 --> 00:51:43.810
And it was interesting in
reading that IPCC report,

00:51:43.810 --> 00:51:46.921
it was very clear there wasn't
a lot of good literature yet

00:51:46.921 --> 00:51:48.170
being brought to bear on that.

00:51:48.170 --> 00:51:49.730
So there's a lot
of wide-open areas

00:51:49.730 --> 00:51:52.130
for people to do research
and new inquiry on,

00:51:52.130 --> 00:51:54.140
and to keep this
interdisciplinary conversation

00:51:54.140 --> 00:51:54.720
going.

00:51:54.720 --> 00:51:55.490
So I thank you.

00:51:55.490 --> 00:51:57.491
Thank you.

00:51:57.491 --> 00:51:58.490
Thank you all very much.

00:51:58.490 --> 00:52:00.290
